Summited Mt Shasta this week. We came out here 2 years ago about same time and had too little snow for good approv v ach and ultimately got blew off the mountain about 12k feet. Came back this year and we’re rewarded with perfect conditions. Few thoughts around the event 
.
1215 am left base camp to make a bid for summit. Started with high excitement if not tired 
.
Near vertical climb for 3k feet to first false summits. I was scared, tired, and worried for the day ahead. @parkermaddox423 had wet boots and had to turn back which was a good decision for the group. Any climber who won’t decide ‘today isn’t the day’ puts everyone in the party at risk. @michaelstevenputnam and I trekked on.
.
Every journey is a step at a time. I kept looking back and could see with my headlamp how steep and how unforgiving it was
.
You’ll never be prepared enough. And you’ll never regret the time and effort you put into preparation. Just like in real life. You can’t fake it at some level
.
We made the 14,100+ summit about 840 am. I took a pic with mike and went to sleep for our 10 min break. We had to get moving because summit is only half way of the climb and we had the most dangerous and hardest parts yet below us. Fatigue and depletion had me deep at this point. I remember looking at mike and thinking ‘he will get me out of here if I need help’ that’s the real truth behind the saying ‘it’s important who you’re in business with’ 
.
We started the long descent. Knowing we had 6-8 hours ahead of us and 8 hours behind us. We roped up the 3 of us for safety. If one slipped it was better to have some anchor to the mountain besides just the axe. The WHOLE way down I was scared. I don’t like descending. I’m always tired and be the descent it’s not dark so you can see just how steep and how dangerous it all looks. On a climb last year I had a equipment failure and couldn’t get it out of my mind on this climb. At one point my crampons were slipping an inch on each step. Being the only way to get up or Down that steep of snow I was terrified. After a reset they were fine but I was still thinking ‘what if’ on every step. 
.
Caution + preparation = safety
.
Adventures are good for the soul
